Trade-off between age of first reproduction and survival in a female primate.

Blomquist GE(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Anthropology, University of Missouri, Columbia, MO 65211, USA. 
blomquistg@missouri.edu

Trade-offs are central to life-history theory but difficult to document. 
Patterns of phenotypic and genetic correlations in rhesus macaques, Macaca 
mulatta-a long-lived, slow-reproducing primate-are used to test for a trade-off 
between female age of first reproduction and adult survival. A strong positive 
genetic correlation indicates that female macaques suffer reduced adult survival 
when they mature relatively early and implies primate senescence can be 
explained, in part, by antagonistic pleiotropy. Contrasts with a similar human 
study implicate the extension of parental effects to later ages as a potential 
mechanism for circumventing female life-history trade-offs in human evolution.

